{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"source": "pdfs/Population-synthesis-using-incomplete-microsample.pdf", "page_numbers": "[4]", "headings": "['3.1.2. Training Data']"}, "page_content": "3.1.2. Training Data\nFor training the proposed WGAN-GP models, we create two different types of training datasets. First, we create a training set that is complete. We sample 10% of the h-population and deliberately remove certain unique category combinations from it. We label this refined dataset as h-nomis . By eliminating certain combinations in h-nomis , we address potential biases in structural zero and sampling zero rates arising from differences in the distributions. Subsequently, we create two incomplete datasets. These datasets are derived from h-nomis but include some attributes with missing information. We randomly selected q numbers of attributes and introduced NaN values randomly to r % of each of the q attributes in the h-nomis dataset. We denote these datasets as h-miss-q-r , which indicates the number of missing attributes and the proportion of rows with NaN values.", "type": "Document"}}